column4: Microsoft shares hit high as cloud business flies above estimates
column5: Microsoft Corp said sales of its flagship cloud product doubled in its first quarter  propelling earnings above analysts' estimates and sending its shares to an all-time high  breaking past a level hit in 1999 at the peak of the tech stock bubble.

column4: BRIEF-Microsoft reports Q1 GAAP earnings of $0.60 per share
column5: * Quarterly diluted earnings per share was $0.60 GAAP  and $0.76 non-GAAP
Oct 20 Microsoft Corp reported a 3.1 percent rise in adjusted revenue on Thursday as growth in its cloud business helped offset weakness in the personal computer market.

column4: Tesla says it will roll out Uber-style ride services program
column5: SAN FRANCISCO Tesla Motors Inc  is planning to roll out a ride services program and will announce details next year  the luxury electric vehicle maker said on its website  a service first outlined by Chief Executive Elon Musk in his master plan in July.

column4: Tesla says self-driving hardware to be built into all its cars
column5: SAN FRANCISCO Chief Executive Elon Musk said on Wednesday all new Tesla Motors Inc  models will come with hardware to enable them to be fully self-driving  as the Silicon Valley electric car company bids to be the first among many rivals to get autonomous vehicles on the road.

column4: Tesla says all vehicles in production to have full self-driving hardware
column5: Oct 19 Electric car maker Tesla Motors Inc  said on Wednesday all vehicles in production  including Model 3  will have full self-driving hardware.

column4: EU court adviser backs Intel fight against record EU fine
column5: LUXEMBOURG/BRUSSELS Intel's  fight against a record 1.06 billion euro  ($1.16 billion) EU antitrust fine received a boost on Thursday when a top Europe court adviser questioned whether the U.S. chipmaker's actions had really harmed competition.

column4: UPDATE 2-EU court adviser backs Intel fight against record EU fine
column5: LUXEMBOURG/BRUSSELS  Oct 20 Intel's  fight against a record 1.06 billion euro  ($1.16 billion) EU antitrust fine received a boost on Thursday when a top Europe court adviser questioned whether the U.S. chipmaker's actions had really harmed competition.

column4: EU court adviser backs Intel appeal against EU fine
column5: LUXEMBOURG  Oct 20 A lower court should review U.S. chipmaker Intel's challenge against a record 1.06-billion-euro ($1.16 billion) fine levied by EU antitrust regulators seven years ago  an adviser to Europe's top court said on Thursday.
